          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">UK joins Indo-Pacific trade bloc</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-16-2.jpg" alt="UK joins Indo-Pacific trade bloc" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The UK has joined the Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership (<a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/explainers-55858490" target="_blank">CPTPP</a>), the largest trade deal since <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-32810887" target="_blank">Brexit</a>. The bloc connects Britain with 11 Indo-Pacific and American nations, including Japan, Australia, and Canada, offering lower tariffs and enhanced trade rules. While the deal includes new trade arrangements with Malaysia and Brunei, its long-term economic benefit is estimated at just £2 billion annually—less than 0.1% of GDP.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Strategically, membership strengthens Britain's ties with the world’s fastest-growing economies. Also, it gives Britain the power to influence the membership of China and Taiwan if they choose to join. Unlike the EU’s single market, the CPTPP isn’t harmonized, maintaining the UK’s trade independence. Costa Rica and Indonesia are now applying for membership, and the bloc's expansion shows it is becoming more globally relevant. The US was a former member, but Donald <a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/business/economy/why-trump-killed-tpp-why-it-matters-you-n710781" target="_blank">Trump pulled them out</a> in 2017 when it was called the Transpacific Partnership; likely, they won’t be rejoining anytime soon with him as president-elect.​</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 12px" />
