          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Diplomat convention</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Major <a href="https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/middle-east-latest-top-diplomats-us-arab-league-116788070" target="_blank">diplomats</a> from the United States, the Arab League, and Turkey met in Jordan over the weekend to discuss Syria’s transition after the dissolution of Bashar al-Assad’s government. The meeting addressed concerns over the potential instability in the region, especially amid ongoing conflicts such as the Israel-Hamas war. Many worry about Syria potentially <a href="https://www.voanews.com/a/7893559.html" target="_blank">fragmenting</a> in the future.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The discussions also <a href="https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/arab-foreign-ministers-urge-support-for-inclusive-peaceful-syria-transition/articleshow/116320771.cms" target="_blank">emphasized</a> the need for an inclusive, Syrian-led transition, including the protection of minorities and the destruction of Assad-era chemical weapons stockpiles. Germany’s foreign minister sent a warning against Assad <a href="https://apnews.com/article/germany-syria-assad-torture-atrocities-warning-99474af63c5a3a0e15bceed2d097f12e" target="_blank">loyalists</a> who committed atrocities by trying to come to Europe. Russia has said it will <a href="https://www.france24.com/en/middle-east/20241214-live-russian-cargo-plane-leaves-syria-for-libya-more-departures-to-come" target="_blank">step back</a>, but not entirely out of Syria. Some countries are warning Syria from forming relations with Israel.</p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>

