          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>🇰🇷 South Korea:</strong>    
          South Korea’s National Assembly voted to <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/live/c1wq025v421t" target="_blank">impeach</a> President Yoon Suk Yeol, citing public outrage over his failed attempt to impose <a href="https://edition.cnn.com/2024/12/03/asia/south-korea-martial-law-explainer-intl-hnk/index.html" target="_blank">martial law</a>. The suspension came after his own People Power Party members voted against him, and the resolution passed with 204 votes. Prime Minister Han Duck-soo is now the acting president, and he promised to stabilize the government, strengthen national security, and address economic concerns. The Constitutional Court has 180 days to decide whether to uphold the impeachment. Yoon described his suspension as “temporary,” pledging to continue serving the country until the end.</p>
        </mj-text>
