          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What was the Berlin conference?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-16-3.jpg" alt="What was the Berlin conference?" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The <a href="https://www.aljazeera.com/opinions/2019/11/15/berlin-1884-remembering-the-conference-that-divided-africa" target="_blank">Berlin Conference</a> (1884-1885) was a pivotal event in which European powers met to regulate the colonization of Africa. German Chancellor Otto von Bismarck organized the conference to avoid conflict between European nations during the “<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DduN1cU2p9U" target="_blank">Scramble for Africa.</a>” Fourteen European countries attended, including Britain, France, Germany, and Belgium, but no African representatives were present.</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The primary outcome was the division of Africa into colonial territories, often without regard for indigenous ethnic or cultural boundaries. The conference introduced the principle of effective occupation, meaning a power had to control a region to claim it physically. It also established free trade along the Congo and Niger rivers.​</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The Berlin Conference helped set the stage for widespread European colonization and reshaped Africa’s political landscape. It left lasting consequences for its people, which can be seen today in African geopolitics.​</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
